8 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
9 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
10 Article – Correctional Services
11 7–202.
12 (a) (1) The Commission consists of [ten] AT LEAST 15 BUT NOT MORE THAN
13 20 members.
14 (2) (I) [With the approval of the] SUBJECT TO SUBPARAGRAPH (III)
15 OF THIS PARAGRAPH, THE Governor [and the advice and consent of the Senate, the
16 Secretary] shall appoint the members of the Commission FROM AMONG NOMINEES
17 CHOSEN BY A PANEL CONSISTING OF:
18 1. THE EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR OF THE MARYLAND
19 POLICE TRAINING AND STANDARDS COMMISSION;
20 2. THE PUBLIC DEFENDER OF MARYLAND;
21 3. THE PRESIDENT OF THE MARYLAND STATE’S
22 ATTORNEYS’ ASSOCIATION;
23 4. THREE SERVICE PROVIDERS FROM THE FIELDS OF
24 MENTAL HEALTH, SUBSTANCE USE TREATMENT, VOCATIONAL AND EDUCATIONAL
25 TRAINING, OR COMMUNITY ORGANIZING, APPOINTED BY THE GOVERNOR;
26 5. THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT OF EDUCATION;
27 6. THE PRESIDENT OF THE NATIONAL ASSOCIATION OF
28 SOCIAL WORKERS – MARYLAND CHAPTER, OR THE PRESIDENT’S DESIGNEE;
29 7. THREE MEMBERS OF THE GENERAL PUBLIC,
30 APPOINTED BY THE GOVERNOR, INCLUDING:

HOUSE BILL 16 3
1 A. AT LEAST ONE MARYLAND RESIDENT WHO WAS
2 FORMERLY INCARCERATED IN A STATE CORRECTIONAL FACILITY; AND
3 B. AT LEAST ONE MARYLAND RESIDENT WHO IS AN
4 IMMEDIATE RELATIVE OF AN INDIVIDUAL WHO IS CURRENTLY, OR WAS FORMERLY,
5 INCARCERATED IN A STATE CORRECTIONAL FACILITY; AND
6 8. ONE PRISONERS’ RIGHTS ADVOCATE, CHOSEN BY THE
7 GOVERNOR; AND
8 9. ONE VICTIM’S RIGHTS ADVOCATE, CHOSEN BY THE
9 GOVERNOR.
10 (II) THE PANEL SHALL SUBMIT TO THE GOVERNOR THE NAMES
11 OF AT LEAST THREE QUALIFIED NOMINEES FOR EACH COMMISSIONER VACANCY TO
12 BE FILLED.
13 (III) THE REQUIREMENT FOR NOMINATION BY THE PANEL
14 UNDER THIS PARAGRAPH APPLIES ONLY TO AN INITIAL TERM AS COMMISSIONER
15 AND NOT TO ANY SUBSEQUENT CONSECUTIVE TERM OF A SITTING COMMISSIONER
16 WHOSE INITIAL APPOINTMENT TO OFFICE WAS MADE PURSUANT TO PANEL
17 NOMINATION.
18 (b) Each commissioner shall:
19 (1) be appointed without regard to political affiliation;
20 (2) be a resident of the State; and
21 (3) have training and experience in law, sociology, psychology, psychiatry,
22 education, social work, or criminology.
23 (c) Each commissioner:
24 (1) shall devote full time to the duties of the Commission; and
25 (2) may not have any other employment that conflicts with the
26 commissioner’s devotion of full time to the duties of the Commission.
27 (d) (1) The term of a commissioner is 6 years.
28 (2) At the end of a term, a commissioner continues to serve until a successor
29 is appointed and qualifies.

4 HOUSE BILL 16
1 (3) A commissioner who is appointed after a term has begun serves only for
2 the rest of the term and until a successor is appointed and qualifies.
3 (e) (1) With the approval of the Governor, the Secretary may remove a
4 commissioner for disability, neglect of duty, or misconduct in office.
5 (2) Before removing a commissioner, the Secretary shall:
6 (i) give the commissioner written notice of the charges against the
7 commissioner; and
8 (ii) hold a public hearing on the charges.
